      <div class="msgContentFrame">There's nothing fame quests did for you by way of getting you to go places and talk to everyone that you couldn't do on your own.  Fame quests in general were the epitome of tedious grind.  &quot;Gather only marginally related item thousands of times and turn in to NPC for mediocre rewards.&quot;  Doesn't fit with a &quot;casual&quot; MMO.  We already get faction credits (same concept, different name) but the process by which we earn them is a bit more...diverse. <br /> <br />I mean sure, turning in enough zinc ore to bury Bastok gave you access to quests out of Norg that allowed you to get some fairly nifty Ninjutsu scrolls, but really?  &quot;Here is an item that does not stack.  You must gather four of these items that do not stack and bring them to &lt;out of the way NPC&gt;...HUNDREDS OF TIMES!! AAAAHAHAHAHA!!  The XIV equivalent would be having to gathering four stacks of puk wings per turn-in and bring them to some prepubescent Lalafel in the farthest corner of Gridania...for 1 faction credit. <br /> <br />The rep grinds in FFXI were borrowed from EQ.  I think the genre is beyond the point where we need to be borrowing concepts from EQ without first evaluating their true merits as entertaining game mechanics.</div>
      <div class="msgFtFrame">
